[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 12.6: Python Implementation Example
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Heads up:** This is a deliberately simple, illustrative implementation of the pseudocode walkthrough from Recipe 12.6. It shows one way you could translate the revenue cycle cash flow forecasting pipeline into working Python using boto3 against Amazon S3 (here represented by a `MockS3` dict), AWS Glue (here represented by an in-process Python harmonization step), Amazon SageMaker (here represented by pure-Python `EmpiricalPaymentCurve`, `KaplanMeierEstimator`, and `PayerHazardModel` classes that stand in for real lifelines, scikit-survival, or DeepAR implementations), AWS Lambda (here represented by a plain Python function that runs the per-claim Monte Carlo sampling), AWS Step Functions (here represented by sequential function calls), Amazon DynamoDB (mocked with `MockTable`), Amazon EventBridge (mocked with `MockEventBus`), and Amazon CloudWatch (mocked with `MockCloudWatch`). The demo generates a synthetic AR ledger covering five payer types (Medicare fee-for-service, a state Medicaid plan, two commercial payers with different contract patterns, and self-pay patient responsibility) with realistic payment-curve shapes, a small denial-and-appeal cycle, and seasonality so you can see the harmonization, the per-payer payment-curve fitting, the per-claim cash-flow simulation, and the weekly aggregation work end-to-end without provisioning anything. It is not production-ready. There is no real S3 bucket, no real Glue ETL, no real SageMaker endpoint, no real Step Functions state machine, no real DynamoDB table, no real EventBridge bus, no real CloudWatch alarms, no integration with an actual 837 claim feed or 835 remittance feed, no contract modeling layer, no per-CPT severity adjustment, no per-Lambda IAM least privilege, no KMS customer-managed keys, no VPC endpoints, no continuous payer drift monitoring, and no recovery-agency or bad-debt write-off modeling. Think of it as the sketchpad version: useful for understanding the shape of a cash flow forecast that respects the per-payer-curve discipline, the survival-modeling discipline, the Monte Carlo composition discipline, and the working-capital framing this recipe demands. It is not something you would point at the CFO's Monday morning treasury meeting. Consider it a starting point, not a destination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > The code maps to the five pseudocode steps from the main recipe: ingest and harmonize the AR ledger, the historical 835 remittance stream, and the payer-contract metadata so every open claim and every historical payment carries a canonical payer identifier, a service date, a billed amount, an expected allowed amount, and a denial flag (Step 1); fit per-payer payment-time distributions from the historical pairs of (claim_submitted_ts, payment_received_ts) using a Kaplan-Meier-style empirical survival estimator with hazard smoothing and right-censoring for still-open claims (Step 2); for every open AR claim, simulate N payment-date samples from the payer-specific distribution conditional on the claim's age and adjudication state, and compose those samples into per-week cash inflow trajectories (Step 3); apply seasonality, denial-and-appeal cycle adjustments, and patient-responsibility tail modeling on top of the per-payer simulations (Step 4); load the surfaced weekly forecasts to DynamoDB keyed by `forecast_week`, write the per-claim sample trajectories to S3 for variance-by-payer analysis, and emit pipeline-lifecycle events to EventBridge (Step 5). The synthetic payers, synthetic AR ledger, and synthetic payment curves in the demo are fictional; nothing in this file should be interpreted as real financial data from any real institution.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Setup
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You will need the AWS SDK for Python:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```bash
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m pip install boto3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The demo runs against the Python standard library plus boto3; no other packages are imported. Production deployments swap the demo's pure-Python estimators for real statistical libraries ([lifelines](https://lifelines.readthedocs.io/) for the Kaplan-Meier survival curves and the Cox proportional-hazards extensions, [scikit-survival](https://scikit-survival.readthedocs.io/) for the gradient-boosted survival models when payer behavior depends on claim-level features, [statsmodels](https://www.statsmodels.org/stable/) for the seasonality decomposition layered on top of the simulations, [NumPy](https://numpy.org/) and [SciPy](https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/) for the vectorized Monte Carlo kernels, the SageMaker [DeepAR built-in algorithm](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sagemaker/latest/dg/deepar.html) for hierarchical multi-payer forecasts that share strength across small-volume payers); the Gap to Production section spells out the substitutions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In production you would also configure an Amazon S3 bucket for the raw 837 claim landing zone, the raw 835 remittance landing zone, the harmonized AR ledger prefix, the per-payer payment-curve prefix, the per-claim sample-trajectory prefix, the weekly forecast prefix, and the model-artifact prefix (one prefix per concern, all SSE-KMS encrypted with a customer-managed key), an AWS Glue job that ingests new 835 files and updates the AR ledger nightly, an Amazon SageMaker training job that refits the per-payer payment curves weekly and writes the artifacts back to S3, an AWS Lambda function that runs the per-claim Monte Carlo simulation across the open AR ledger, an AWS Step Functions state machine that orchestrates the weekly cycle (harmonize -> fit curves -> simulate -> aggregate -> deliver) with retries and `Catch` blocks for transient failures, an Amazon DynamoDB table for the weekly cash flow forecasts keyed by `forecast_week` with the per-payer breakdown as a sort-key sub-record, an Amazon EventBridge schedule that triggers the Step Functions state machine weekly, Amazon CloudWatch dashboards and alarms for pipeline failures, payer-curve drift, forecast-vs-actual variance, and AR aging shifts, and a thin integration layer that exposes the forecasts to the finance team's treasury dashboard or working-capital spreadsheet. The demo replaces all of these with a single in-process Python file so the focus stays on the harmonization, the survival-curve math, the Monte Carlo composition, and the per-week aggregation rather than on the platform plumbing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Your environment needs credentials configured (via environment variables, an instance profile, or `~/.aws/credentials`). The IAM role or user needs:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `s3:GetObject` and `s3:PutObject` on the raw-claim prefix, the raw-remittance prefix, the harmonized AR ledger prefix, the payer-curve prefix, the sample-trajectory prefix, the weekly forecast prefix, and the model-artifact prefix
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `glue:StartJobRun` and `glue:GetJobRun` on the AR ingestion Glue job, plus the Glue service role's permissions for the ETL job
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob`, `sagemaker:DescribeTrainingJob`, `sagemaker:CreateModel`, `sagemaker:CreateEndpointConfig`, `sagemaker:UpdateEndpoint`, and `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint` on the per-payer payment-curve models
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `lambda:InvokeFunction` on the Monte Carlo simulation Lambda
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `dynamodb:BatchWriteItem`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:UpdateItem`, `dynamodb:Query`, and `dynamodb:GetItem` on the `cash-flow-forecasts` table, scoped to the specific table ARN
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `events:PutEvents` on the cash-flow-events bus for emitting pipeline-lifecycle events (run started, curves fit, simulation completed, forecast written, drift alarm raised)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `states:StartExecution` on the cash-flow Step Functions state machine for the weekly forecast run
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `cloudwatch:PutMetricData` for the operational metrics (per-payer simulated mean payment lag, per-payer denial rate, forecast variance vs. actuals, AR aging buckets, weekly forecast error)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `kms:Decrypt` and `kms:GenerateDataKey` on the customer-managed keys protecting the S3 prefixes, the DynamoDB table, and the model-artifact bucket
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Scope each Lambda's IAM role to the specific resource ARNs it touches. The tutorial-level permissions above are fine for learning and will fail any serious IAM review. The Glue ingestion job has read access to the raw-remittance prefix and write access to the harmonized AR ledger prefix, but no DynamoDB or SageMaker permissions. The Monte Carlo Lambda has read access to the payer-curve prefix and the AR ledger prefix, plus write access to the sample-trajectory prefix and the weekly forecast DynamoDB table, but no raw-claim permissions. Avoid wildcard actions and resources in production.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things worth knowing upfront:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Revenue-cycle data is PHI by association.** A claim record carries patient identifier, service date, CPT code, ICD code, billed amount, payer, allowed amount, denial reason, and a free-text remit memo. Aggregated cash forecasts derived from these claims are still PHI when they retain any patient-level granularity. Every storage and compute service that touches this pipeline must be on the [HIPAA eligible services](https://aws.amazon.com/compliance/hipaa-eligible-services-reference/) list, every storage layer must be encrypted with customer-managed KMS keys, every network hop must be inside the institutional VPC with no public path, and CloudTrail must log every data-plane API call. Even when the surfaced forecast is "expected cash for week of 2026-06-01 = $4.2M," the upstream join keys remain PHI.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Each payer is its own time series.** Medicare fee-for-service pays differently from Medicaid, Medicaid pays differently from a commercial insurer, and a commercial insurer with a delegated-risk contract pays differently from one with a fee-for-service contract. The pipeline forecasts each payer independently and then aggregates, because mixing them produces a model that learns the average curve and is wrong for every payer in different ways.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Time-to-payment is a survival problem, not a regression problem.** A claim submitted today either pays in 14 days, or 28 days, or 45 days, or it gets denied and the denial-appeal cycle resets the clock. The right framing is a survival curve: probability of payment by day d. Open claims are right-censored (you have not yet observed their payment date) and the estimator has to handle that.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The denial cycle is a separate sub-process.** First-pass denials happen on roughly 5 to 12% of claims for most provider organizations. Of those, 60 to 80% are recoverable through appeal, and the appeal adds 30 to 90 days to the payment timeline. The pipeline either models this as a two-stage process (first-pass payment curve plus a denial-and-appeal sub-curve) or rolls it into the headline curve at the cost of less interpretability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Patient responsibility is its own animal.** After the primary payer adjudicates, whatever the patient owes (deductible, coinsurance, copay) shifts to the patient AR bucket, which has dramatically different dynamics. Self-pay AR has long tails, low recovery rates, and is sensitive to statement cycle, payment-plan availability, and the presence or absence of pre-collection workflows. Production pipelines either model self-pay separately or accept that the self-pay tail is the dominant uncertainty in the longer-horizon forecast.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Contract changes break the model overnight.** A new fee schedule with a major payer, a renegotiated denial-appeal escalation path, a switch from delegated risk to fee-for-service, all of these shift the payment curve in ways the historical data does not predict. The pipeline needs an explicit contract-effective-date awareness so the curves train only on data after the relevant contract took effect, and an alert when the live data starts to diverge from the trained curve.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **DynamoDB rejects Python `float`.** Every dollar amount, probability, day count, and percentile passes through `Decimal` on its way in and on its way out. The `_to_decimal` helper handles it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The example collapses many Lambdas, Glue jobs, and SageMaker endpoints into a single Python file.** In production the AR ingestion Glue job, the curve-fitting SageMaker training job, the Monte Carlo Lambda, the aggregation Lambda, and the DynamoDB-loader Lambda are separate units of work with their own IAM roles, error handling, retries, and DLQs. Comments call out where the boundaries should fall.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Configuration and Constants
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Everything that is configuration rather than logic lives here. Resource names, the payer catalog, the per-payer denial-and-appeal parameters, the seasonality factors, the Monte Carlo sample count, and the synthetic-data parameters are what you would change between environments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import logging
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import math
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import random
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import uuid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from collections import defaultdict
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from datetime import date, datetime, timedelta, timezone
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from decimal import Decimal
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from statistics import mean, median, stdev
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import boto3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from botocore.config import Config
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Structured logging. In production, ship JSON-formatted records
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # to CloudWatch Logs Insights for cross-call investigation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Revenue-cycle records are PHI by association; log structural
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # metadata only (run_id, payer_id, claim_count, total_amount_band,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # runtime_ms), never raw claim numbers, never patient identifiers,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # never service dates tied to identifiable encounters, never the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # per-claim denial-reason text.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m logger.setLevel(logging.INFO)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Adaptive retry handles throttling from S3, DynamoDB, EventBridge,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # CloudWatch, and SageMaker. The weekly cash-flow pipeline is a
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # scheduled batch job that touches every open claim, so retries
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # should be quick and capped. A stuck dependency must not balloon
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # a 30-minute weekly window into a multi-hour incident that blocks
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # the Monday morning treasury review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG = Config(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     retries={"max_attempts": 5, "mode": "adaptive"})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Module-level clients. Reused across function calls within the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # pipeline so each call does not pay the connection cost. The
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # demo wires up MockS3 / MockTable / MockEventBus / MockCloudWatch
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # via run_demo() and never touches these real handles; they are
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # staged here so production wiring is a one-line swap. boto3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # client and resource construction is lazy (no network call until
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # first use), so the unused handles are free at import.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m REGION = "us-east-1"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m s3_client          = boto3.client("s3",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m dynamodb           = boto3.resource("dynamodb",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                     region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                     config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m eventbridge_client = boto3.client("events",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m cloudwatch_client  = boto3.client("cloudwatch",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m sagemaker_runtime  = boto3.client("sagemaker-runtime",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m lambda_client      = boto3.client("lambda",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                   config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Resource Names ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Fill these in with your actual resource names. The demo prints
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # what it would write rather than failing if the resources do
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # not exist; see run_demo() at the bottom.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m RAW_CLAIM_BUCKET           = "rcm-cash-flow-raw-837"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m RAW_REMIT_BUCKET           = "rcm-cash-flow-raw-835"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m HARMONIZED_AR_BUCKET       = "rcm-cash-flow-ar-ledger"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m PAYER_CURVE_BUCKET         = "rcm-cash-flow-payer-curves"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SAMPLE_TRAJECTORY_BUCKET   = "rcm-cash-flow-sample-trajectories"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FORECAST_BUCKET            = "rcm-cash-flow-forecasts"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m MODEL_ARTIFACT_BUCKET      = "rcm-cash-flow-models"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CASH_FORECAST_TABLE        = "cash-flow-forecasts"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CASH_FORECAST_EVENT_BUS    = "cash-flow-events-bus"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CLOUDWATCH_NAMESPACE       = "RevenueCycleCashFlow"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Versioning ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Every weekly forecast carries the model version and the contract
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # library version active at the time of generation. This is how
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # a future audit reconstructs which curves and which contract
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # assumptions produced which forecast on which week.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m PIPELINE_VERSION         = "cash-flow-v1.3"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CONTRACT_LIBRARY_VERSION = "contracts-2026-Q2"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Forecast Parameters ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # 13-week (one quarter) horizon is the default for cash-flow
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # forecasts because that is the standard treasury-planning window.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # 26-week and 52-week variants are reasonable extensions; the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # longer the horizon, the more the patient-responsibility tail
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # dominates the uncertainty.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m DEFAULT_HORIZON_WEEKS         = 13
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m DEFAULT_MONTE_CARLO_SAMPLES   = 1000
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m DEFAULT_HISTORY_LOOKBACK_DAYS = 365 * 2
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Payer Catalog ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Per-payer configuration covering the small panel the demo
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # operates on. Production maintains a curated table with hundreds
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # of entries managed by the institutional revenue-cycle team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Each entry carries: the canonical payer identifier, the payer
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # class (medicare / medicaid / commercial / self_pay / wc_auto),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # the typical first-pass denial rate, the appeal recovery rate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # (probability that a denied claim is recovered through appeal),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # the appeal lag in days, the contract effective date (curves
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # train only on data after this), and the display name for
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # surfaced payloads.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m PAYER_CATALOG = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "MEDI-FFS-001": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "display":               "Medicare FFS",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "payer_class":           "medicare",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "first_pass_denial_rate": 0.04,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "appeal_recovery_rate":   0.65,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "appeal_lag_days_mean":   45,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "appeal_lag_days_sd":     12,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "contract_effective_date": "2024-01-01",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "MCAID-STATE-001": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "display":               "State Medicaid",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "payer_class":           "medicaid",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "first_pass_denial_rate": 0.09,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "appeal_recovery_rate":   0.55,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "appeal_lag_days_mean":   60,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "appeal_lag_days_sd":     18,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "contract_effective_date": "2025-07-01",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "COMM-BCBS-001": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "display":               "Commercial BCBS Plan",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "payer_class":           "commercial",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "first_pass_denial_rate": 0.07,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "appeal_recovery_rate":   0.70,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "appeal_lag_days_mean":   38,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "appeal_lag_days_sd":     10,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "contract_effective_date": "2025-10-01",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "COMM-NATIONAL-001": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "display":               "Commercial National Plan",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "payer_class":           "commercial",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "first_pass_denial_rate": 0.11,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "appeal_recovery_rate":   0.60,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "appeal_lag_days_mean":   42,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "appeal_lag_days_sd":     11,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "contract_effective_date": "2025-04-01",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "SELF-PAY-001": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "display":               "Self-Pay / Patient Responsibility",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "payer_class":           "self_pay",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "first_pass_denial_rate": 0.0,    # no formal denials, just non-payment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "appeal_recovery_rate":   0.0,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "appeal_lag_days_mean":   0,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "appeal_lag_days_sd":     0,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "contract_effective_date": "2020-01-01",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Seasonality and Calendar ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Multiplicative seasonality factors applied at the per-week
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # aggregation step. Production fits these from data using an
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # STL or X-13ARIMA-SEATS decomposition; the demo uses fixed
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # illustrative factors that capture the typical "Medicare and
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Medicaid pay slower in late December and early January due
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # to year-end claim re-routing" pattern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SEASONALITY_BY_WEEK_OF_YEAR = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     1:  0.92, 2:  0.95, 3:  0.98, 4:  1.00,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     52: 0.88, 51: 0.90, 50: 0.95,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     27: 0.96, 28: 0.97,    # 4th of July week typically a bit slower
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- AR Aging Buckets ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Standard healthcare AR aging buckets for surfaced reporting.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # The forecast surfaces aging-bucket-conditional probabilities
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # so the finance team sees not just total expected cash but
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # how much of it comes from "fresh" AR vs. "old" AR.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m AR_AGING_BUCKETS = [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("0-30",   0,   30),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("31-60",  31,  60),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("61-90",  61,  90),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("91-120", 91,  120),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("121+",   121, 9999),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Synthetic Data ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Knobs for the demo's synthetic-history generator. The ranges
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # produce a small but realistic-shaped two-year history with
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # five payers so you can see the pipeline fit per-payer curves
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # and forecast cash by week.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SYNTHETIC_HISTORICAL_DAYS = DEFAULT_HISTORY_LOOKBACK_DAYS
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SYNTHETIC_OPEN_AR_COUNT   = 800
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SYNTHETIC_RANDOM_SEED     = 42
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Deploy-time guardrail. Any blank resource name is a deploy-time
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # bug, not a runtime surprise.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m for _name, _value in [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("RAW_CLAIM_BUCKET",         RAW_CLAIM_BUCKET),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("RAW_REMIT_BUCKET",         RAW_REMIT_BUCKET),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("HARMONIZED_AR_BUCKET",     HARMONIZED_AR_BUCKET),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("PAYER_CURVE_BUCKET",       PAYER_CURVE_BUCKET),
